    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tiny, plump, wingless, slate-blue animal covered with short hydrophobic hairs which allow it to float on the water surface. The head has small eyes and short antennae, the thorax three pairs of short, stumpy legs and the abdomen six plump segments. The ventral furca, which is the most distinctive feature of most collembolans, is vestigial in this species, which thus is unable to jump.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_316",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 3 mm.<i>&nbsp;</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_317",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2889-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2889-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-2889-1000.webp"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Cosmopolitan.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Throughout the region, mostly on intertidal rocks.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_318",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common in the upper intertidal zone on both rocky shores and saltmarshes, boulder beaches, etc. Shelters in cavities such as rock crevices and dead barnacle shells when the tide is in and emerges at low tide to scavenge dead animals. Often see floating in rafts of many individuals together on the surfaces of high-shore rock pools.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_319",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feed on dead or dying animal material, such as barnacles, drowning beach-hoppers, etc.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_320",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Males deposit a spermatophore on the substratum and the females move over this and pick it up to fertilise their eggs. Eggs are laid in shelters and hatch directly into the adult form.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_321",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Although there are many other collembolans in the region, including some found on the surface of freshwater, this is the only species so far reported from rocky shores. The fact that it does not leap, which is so characteristic of most other springtails, also is a useful aid to identification.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_322",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "McMeechan, FK, Manica, A, & Foster, WA (2000). Rhythms of activity and foraging in the intertidal insect Anurida maritima: coping with the tide. <i>Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom</i>, 80(1), 189-190.<br><br>Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town (p. 74).",
